\begin_layout Enumerate
The denominator of the Rayleigh quotient is 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u_{a},u_{a}\rangle=\int_{0}^{a}(x/a)^{2}dx+\int_{a}^{1}(1-x)^{2}/(1-a)^{2}dx=a/3+(1-a)/3=1/3$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative is 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{a}'(x)=1/a$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\leq a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1/(1-a)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x>a$
\end_inset

, so the numerator of the Rayleigh quotient is 
\begin_inset Formula $\langle u_{a}',u_{a}'\rangle=\int_{0}^{a}(1/a)^{2}dx+\int_{a}^{1}1/(1-a)^{2}dx=\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{1-a}$
\end_inset

, and hence 
\begin_inset Formula \[
R(u_{a})=3\left(\frac{1}{a}+\frac{1}{1-a}\right),\]

\end_inset

which is maximized when 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dR}{da}=\frac{3}{(1-a)^{2}}-\frac{3}{a^{2}}=0$
\end_inset

, and hence at 
\begin_inset Formula $\boxed{a=1/2}$
\end_inset

.
 The minimum is then 
\begin_inset Formula $R(u_{1/2})=12$
\end_inset

, which is a bit bigger than the smallest eigenvalue 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi^{2}\approx9.8696$
\end_inset

 (it is the right order of magnitude anyway, and as expected 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 cannot be 
\emph on
smaller
\emph default
 than the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

).
 
