\begin_layout Standard
Since this function has two discontinuities, at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=\pm\Delta x$
\end_inset

, and is otherwise constant, the derivative is simply two delta functions
 multiplied by the respective amplitudes of the discontinuities: 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s'_{\Delta x}=\frac{1}{2\Delta x}\left[\delta(x-\Delta x)-\delta(x+\Delta x)\right],\]

\end_inset

which can also be seen by writing 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\Delta x}(x)=\frac{1}{2\Delta x}\left[S(x-\Delta x)-S(x+\Delta x)\right]$
\end_inset

 in terms of the unit step function 
\begin_inset Formula $S(x)$
\end_inset

 from the notes and then applying the rule for differentiating 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 as a distribution.
 Hence, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s'_{\Delta x}\{\phi\}=\frac{1}{2\Delta x}\left[\phi(-\Delta x)-\phi(\Delta x)\right].\]

\end_inset

But this is exactly a center-difference approximation for 
\begin_inset Formula $-\phi'(0)$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lim_{\Delta x\to0}s'_{\Delta x}\{\phi\}=-\lim_{\Delta x\to0}\frac{\phi(\Delta x)-\phi(-\Delta x)}{2\Delta x}=-\phi'(0)=\delta'\{\phi\}\]

\end_inset

as desired.
